ous practice during the U.S. occupation between 1916 and 1924; the massacre of more than 20,000 people on the Dominican-Haitian border in 1937; and the 2010 earthquake in Haiti. García-Peña also considers the contemporary emergence of a broader Dominican consciousness among artists and intellectuals that offers alternative perspectives to questions of identity as well as the means to make audible the voices of long-silenced Dominicans.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aBlacksxRace identityzDominican Republic. 0aDominican AmericansxRace identity. 0aImmigrantszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aRace in mass media. 7aHISTORY / Caribbean & West Indies / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070808040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822373667zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822373667423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822373667.jpg  a978-3-11-070808-0  DUK Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles